Diploma thesis:
Abstract
This thesis deals with performance optimisation in standalone virtual reality applications and uses the Villa Stiassni VR project as a case study. The work focuses on the specific constraints of mobile VR hardware, where stable frame time, limited memory, and predictable rendering cost are essential for user comfort and application usability. The theoretical part introduces the main areas relevant to VR optimisation, including target hardware, rendering constraints, asset preparation, lighting, physics, interaction systems, and common Unity optimisation techniques. The practical part applies selected techniques to the Villa Stiassni project and evaluates their effect on Meta Quest hardware. The tested changes include occlusion culling, level-of-detail systems, baked lightmaps, Adaptive Probe Volumes, reflection probes, texture and material optimisation, and platform-specific project settings. The results show that occlusion culling produced the clearest performance improvement by reducing unnecessary rendering work and improving frame-time stability in the indoor scene. Level-of-detail systems were less significant in the measured traversal but remain useful for scalability. Baked lightmaps provided a balance between runtime performance and memory usage, while Adaptive Probe Volumes helped with lighting consistency on lower-detail geometry. The textured variants showed that richer visual presentation can remain stable when supported by a suitable optimisation workflow. The thesis concludes that standalone VR optimisation is not a single isolated step, but a continuous process of balancing visibility, geometry, lighting, materials, memory usage, and visual quality. The case study demonstrates that targeted optimisation can improve runtime stability and create performance headroom for future development of the Villa Stiassni application.

